01:46:23.320 --> 01:46:26.240
There are two selves to talk about, too.

01:46:26.240 --> 01:46:30.200
There's the sort of self that seems connected to experience, even if it's a very kind of

01:46:30.200 --> 01:46:37.360
loose sense of identity just in an instant or a kind of self-identity that persists over

01:46:37.360 --> 01:46:41.160
time for which we experience it as relatively continuous.

01:46:41.160 --> 01:46:46.120
But when you have an injury or you black out, then you sort of, there's a discontinuous

01:46:46.120 --> 01:46:47.560
personal identity over time.

01:46:47.560 --> 01:46:53.720
So then there are philosophers who do think that any experience of consciousness sort

01:46:53.720 --> 01:46:57.160
of has to have that at center of gravity, a self.

01:46:57.160 --> 01:47:00.160
And then there are others who don't.

01:47:00.160 --> 01:47:09.120
I wanted to bring up an aspect of consciousness that seems pretty important to me, but I don't

01:47:09.120 --> 01:47:15.160
think anyone's really raised this, but the moral implications of consciousness.

01:47:15.160 --> 01:47:20.440
I mean, I think all of us think that it's probably wrong to hurt other human beings,

01:47:20.440 --> 01:47:25.480
but it's probably not wrong maybe to pull the plug on someone who's already like in a

01:47:25.480 --> 01:47:31.040
maybe comatose state or something, but then many people believe because animals have

